1
00:00:07,679 --> 00:00:09,960
Okay, hello everyone.

2
00:00:09,960 --> 00:00:11,460
Wow, that's just amazing.

3
00:00:11,460 --> 00:00:13,901
So many people here, it's incredible.

4
00:00:13,901 --> 00:00:15,281
I'm super excited to be here.

5
00:00:15,281 --> 00:00:17,082
My name is Joanna Piecka, I'm a computer scientist

6
00:00:17,082 --> 00:00:18,362
and game developer from Austria.

7
00:00:18,362 --> 00:00:20,463
That's because of my strong accent, you might know.

8
00:00:20,463 --> 00:00:23,864
And I've heard, I was very nervous about this talk,

9
00:00:23,864 --> 00:00:26,704
but someone told me, I just need to inspire people

10
00:00:26,704 --> 00:00:31,106
with my talk in a soapbox and do a lot of frantic,

11
00:00:31,106 --> 00:00:32,646
and then I'm gonna be fine.

12
00:00:32,646 --> 00:00:33,766
So I tried to do both.

13
00:00:34,307 --> 00:00:37,971
And I would like to start with my backstory.

14
00:00:37,971 --> 00:00:43,678
So I think everyone of us noticed a moment when you're, I don't know, you're out of motivation,

15
00:00:43,678 --> 00:00:45,521
you're not inspired anymore.

16
00:00:45,521 --> 00:00:50,487
And I had this phase also a couple of years ago and I was stuck.

17
00:00:50,487 --> 00:00:51,388
I was stuck.

18
00:00:51,969 --> 00:00:59,274
And I didn't have any inspiration and I was stuck not only in developing games, but also in playing games.

19
00:00:59,274 --> 00:01:04,939
So I played games all the time from the same genre, from the same developer.

20
00:01:04,939 --> 00:01:07,361
I played those games from the same platform.

21
00:01:07,361 --> 00:01:11,684
And I thought, okay, I'm stuck also in playing games, how can I develop any new games?

22
00:01:12,175 --> 00:01:15,676
And I really tried to find new game mechanics,

23
00:01:15,676 --> 00:01:17,237
but playing always the same games

24
00:01:17,237 --> 00:01:18,457
doesn't make any sense for that.

25
00:01:18,457 --> 00:01:21,718
So I thought I should try out something totally new,

26
00:01:21,718 --> 00:01:23,178
get out of my comfort zone,

27
00:01:23,178 --> 00:01:27,979
try games which I would never play in other circumstances.

28
00:01:27,979 --> 00:01:30,100
And I thought getting out of this comfort zone

29
00:01:30,100 --> 00:01:31,960
would eventually help me learning

30
00:01:31,960 --> 00:01:34,161
and getting my inspiration back again.

31
00:01:35,201 --> 00:01:39,644
And so I wanted to combine it with something which I really like, and I love to travel.

32
00:01:39,644 --> 00:01:45,989
I'm one of those crazy backpacking persons, trying to see all the countries,

33
00:01:45,989 --> 00:01:47,530
and I would always buy a travel guide.

34
00:01:47,530 --> 00:01:53,315
And if you look at a travel guide, you would get a list of things you should do in this country,

35
00:01:53,315 --> 00:01:59,039
monuments you should visit, food you should try, movies you should watch,

36
00:01:59,039 --> 00:02:02,201
everything to get the whole experience for this country.

37
00:02:02,201 --> 00:02:04,603
But you never get an experience for games you should play.

38
00:02:05,514 --> 00:02:08,637
But I believe that our games are cultural goods as well.

39
00:02:08,637 --> 00:02:12,440
And people should think of this and should add those

40
00:02:12,440 --> 00:02:14,242
to the travel guides.

41
00:02:14,242 --> 00:02:16,364
I believe our games are fantastic for that.

42
00:02:16,364 --> 00:02:17,825
They should be relevant.

43
00:02:17,825 --> 00:02:21,128
And that's why I tried to start a project, which I call

44
00:02:21,128 --> 00:02:22,950
A Year of Playing the World.

45
00:02:22,950 --> 00:02:25,272
And I tried to find and play games

46
00:02:25,272 --> 00:02:27,974
from all the different countries of the world, which

47
00:02:27,974 --> 00:02:29,195
are roughly 200.

48
00:02:30,479 --> 00:02:33,001
So I try to find and approach developers

49
00:02:33,001 --> 00:02:35,764
and community people from the countries

50
00:02:35,764 --> 00:02:37,446
and would ask them always the same question.

51
00:02:37,446 --> 00:02:40,390
If there is one game I should play

52
00:02:40,390 --> 00:02:43,393
developed in your country, which one should it be?

53
00:02:43,393 --> 00:02:46,296
Ask yourself as well, it's quite an interesting question.

54
00:02:46,296 --> 00:02:46,997
Pretty challenging.

55
00:02:48,005 --> 00:02:52,370
And I got a list full of inspirational games.

56
00:02:52,370 --> 00:02:56,274
And I was inspired by environments, by strong characters,

57
00:02:56,274 --> 00:02:59,658
by really cool stories, and by fancy mechanics.

58
00:02:59,658 --> 00:03:03,102
But most interesting, it wasn't the games

59
00:03:03,102 --> 00:03:05,745
with the fancy mechanics which inspired me most.

60
00:03:06,510 --> 00:03:11,592
It was games which were relevant to the culture or to the countries or to the regions.

61
00:03:11,592 --> 00:03:18,034
And I want to give you some ideas for inspirations how to also create really interesting games that way.

62
00:03:18,034 --> 00:03:26,998
So maybe create a game with cultural relevance like they did in the game A Year Walk, a Swedish game,

63
00:03:26,998 --> 00:03:31,820
where they use Swedish traditions which they taught through this game.

64
00:03:33,301 --> 00:03:41,147
Or tell personal stories relevant to your region, like Abdullah did in the game Pathout.

65
00:03:41,147 --> 00:03:47,251
He actually tells the story how he escaped the Syrian war in 2014.

66
00:03:47,251 --> 00:03:54,096
And he makes it even more personal, it's a very dramatic story, by adding YouTube-style comments to that.

67
00:03:55,748 --> 00:04:00,870
or something more fun, find and spread local fun stories,

68
00:04:00,870 --> 00:04:05,471
local gems, local stories which are only known in this region.

69
00:04:05,471 --> 00:04:07,772
So for example, this guy, the game

70
00:04:07,772 --> 00:04:12,254
is called KnÃ¶delkrieg in German, Dumpling War in English.

71
00:04:12,254 --> 00:04:14,755
And there was a Bavarian man who was really

72
00:04:14,755 --> 00:04:17,716
upset about the noise the aircrafts were making

73
00:04:17,716 --> 00:04:19,896
very close to his house.

74
00:04:19,896 --> 00:04:20,577
This was 1967.

75
00:04:20,577 --> 00:04:25,178
And he decided to fight back by throwing dumplings at them.

76
00:04:28,887 --> 00:04:34,411
But looking at those games, I also found a lot of issues and problems.

77
00:04:34,411 --> 00:04:39,775
And one really big issue, I think we are developing games in a wrong way.

78
00:04:39,775 --> 00:04:43,658
Because we are not treating our games in a cultural good way.

79
00:04:43,658 --> 00:04:48,682
We don't think of them as something which should be also preserved in 10 years or 100

80
00:04:48,682 --> 00:04:49,402
years.

81
00:04:49,402 --> 00:04:53,505
Some of the games I was trying to play were not even playable after one year anymore.

82
00:04:53,965 --> 00:04:55,767
And now think of all the controllers

83
00:04:55,767 --> 00:04:58,089
we're having right now, the engines we are using.

84
00:04:58,089 --> 00:05:01,892
What will the controllers of the future look like?

85
00:05:01,892 --> 00:05:04,274
Can we play our games in 10 years still?

86
00:05:04,274 --> 00:05:07,017
And if it's cultural good, we need

87
00:05:07,017 --> 00:05:09,479
to think of ways of to solve this problem.

88
00:05:09,479 --> 00:05:13,462
So develop your games with more care for the future.

89
00:05:13,462 --> 00:05:16,645
And please find inspiration by my list

90
00:05:16,645 --> 00:05:19,688
of the games from different countries on my website.

91
00:05:19,688 --> 00:05:20,728
Thank you.

92
00:05:31,214 --> 00:05:33,876
Thank you, Joanna.

93
00:05:33,876 --> 00:05:35,158
Hang on one sec.

94
00:05:35,158 --> 00:05:41,403
You're just too fast, Davey.

95
00:05:41,403 --> 00:05:42,464
That's what...

96
00:05:42,464 --> 00:05:44,586
Don't do it.

97
00:05:44,586 --> 00:05:45,767
Hi, I'm on video camera.

98
00:05:45,767 --> 00:05:49,630
All right, please welcome Davey.

99
00:05:55,970 --> 00:05:56,770
There it is.

100
00:05:56,770 --> 00:05:58,692
Hi there, my name is Davey Readon.

101
00:05:58,692 --> 00:06:00,674
I was the creator of The Stanley Parable,

102
00:06:00,674 --> 00:06:02,896
The Beginner's Guide, and absolutely,

103
00:06:02,896 --> 00:06:05,318
A True Crime Story featuring Keanu Reeves.

104
00:06:05,318 --> 00:06:07,219
Today, I wanna talk just a little bit

105
00:06:07,219 --> 00:06:08,661
about some of the game design questions

106
00:06:08,661 --> 00:06:10,102
that have been on my mind lately

107
00:06:10,102 --> 00:06:12,104
and some of the goals that I'm shooting for.

108
00:06:13,125 --> 00:06:18,230
One of the ways that I really like to work is by setting myself these very impossible-sounding goals

109
00:06:18,230 --> 00:06:21,114
and then figuring out how I can actually pull it off.

110
00:06:21,114 --> 00:06:24,758
So I don't necessarily have answers to these questions just yet,

111
00:06:24,758 --> 00:06:27,040
but I thought I'd put them to you and see what you think.

112
00:06:27,821 --> 00:06:33,187
So, I've been thinking a lot about why people continue playing a game after they've started.

113
00:06:33,187 --> 00:06:37,531
This is if we are assuming that the game is at least somewhat fun or interesting on a

114
00:06:37,531 --> 00:06:43,037
core mechanical level, and if so, why does a person want to put in hour after hour on

115
00:06:43,037 --> 00:06:47,601
this one game as opposed to playing a different game or doing something else with their life

116
00:06:47,601 --> 00:06:48,062
entirely?

117
00:06:48,062 --> 00:06:51,105
Basically, what creates their engagement?

118
00:06:51,625 --> 00:06:56,351
And for the purpose of this talk, I'm really only talking about single player games, socializing

119
00:06:56,351 --> 00:07:02,518
and competition in multiplayer games are sort of like their whole own separate motivators.

120
00:07:02,518 --> 00:07:08,304
So after a lot of thought, here's my personal interpretation, just mine, of why people continue

121
00:07:08,304 --> 00:07:12,288
playing a game distilled into three extremely broad categories.

122
00:07:13,490 --> 00:07:16,051
One is to become better or to optimize.

123
00:07:16,051 --> 00:07:21,195
It's the enjoyable feeling that you are better now at the game than you were when you started playing.

124
00:07:21,195 --> 00:07:28,021
Number two is to make progress, watching your number go up or gaining more items or more stuff.

125
00:07:28,021 --> 00:07:35,827
And number three is to see more content, because we like the story, we like the characters, we like the world, and we want to continue to see more of it.

126
00:07:37,064 --> 00:07:43,852
So to me, these three things sum up what like 99.9% of games out there today are doing to

127
00:07:43,852 --> 00:07:46,075
create engagement with their players.

128
00:07:46,075 --> 00:07:49,860
And this is really cool and we know that this is effective on some level and it can be a

129
00:07:49,860 --> 00:07:51,742
lot of fun and we all like games like this.

130
00:07:52,122 --> 00:07:55,223
So the question that I've been grappling with a lot lately is,

131
00:07:55,223 --> 00:07:58,764
how could you make a game that is engaging and compelling

132
00:07:58,764 --> 00:08:02,246
and that does not, at its core, rely on any of these three

133
00:08:02,246 --> 00:08:06,047
things to make you interested?

134
00:08:06,047 --> 00:08:08,928
And by the way, I'm not saying none of them,

135
00:08:08,928 --> 00:08:12,489
but what could you do to not have them be the core

136
00:08:12,489 --> 00:08:15,370
and then bring in other things and then bring these things in

137
00:08:15,370 --> 00:08:17,651
later on once there is another core?

138
00:08:18,751 --> 00:08:23,415
I think one of the things with these three things is, with these three points, is that

139
00:08:23,415 --> 00:08:27,519
they all rely on something outside the act of play itself to be interesting.

140
00:08:27,519 --> 00:08:33,043
With the first, you're imagining a better, a future version of yourself who is better

141
00:08:33,043 --> 00:08:33,584
at the game.

142
00:08:33,584 --> 00:08:37,587
With the second, you're imagining a future where your number is bigger.

143
00:08:37,587 --> 00:08:41,611
With the third, you're imagining how cool it'll be to see the rest of the story.

144
00:08:41,611 --> 00:08:43,853
So in a way, they're all future motivated.

145
00:08:43,973 --> 00:08:49,095
and I would love to explore play that is engaging and compelling in this very moment

146
00:08:49,095 --> 00:08:52,856
without that reliance on the future in order to provide the value.

147
00:08:52,856 --> 00:08:58,498
I think that if I say this, right off the bat, a lot of people would say,

148
00:08:58,498 --> 00:09:00,279
that sounds like a toy.

149
00:09:00,279 --> 00:09:02,580
And yes, this is typically how we think of toys,

150
00:09:02,580 --> 00:09:06,481
is as a device that has no function except the intrinsic act of play.

151
00:09:06,481 --> 00:09:12,003
But usually we draw a kind of ideological line between a toy and a video game.

152
00:09:12,724 --> 00:09:16,085
And we think of a game as having a point or a context

153
00:09:16,085 --> 00:09:19,766
that elevates it above the act of just play itself.

154
00:09:19,766 --> 00:09:22,367
So the weird goal that I'm setting for myself

155
00:09:22,367 --> 00:09:26,309
is to create a game that is intrinsically fun to play

156
00:09:26,309 --> 00:09:28,970
and that has the kind of context that would make us say,

157
00:09:28,970 --> 00:09:32,351
this is a video game, but that does not at its core

158
00:09:32,351 --> 00:09:35,412
rely on any of these three things to be compelling.

159
00:09:35,412 --> 00:09:37,793
And like I said, I think that they can still be there,

160
00:09:37,793 --> 00:09:40,414
but could they be something other than the soul

161
00:09:40,414 --> 00:09:41,015
and direct?

162
00:09:41,335 --> 00:09:43,537
reason why you would want to continue playing at all.

163
00:09:43,537 --> 00:09:48,841
So for example, what would a game be like that offered you interesting choices, but

164
00:09:48,841 --> 00:09:54,345
you can't actually get better at making those choices, or you can't make more optimized

165
00:09:54,345 --> 00:09:55,226
choices?

166
00:09:55,226 --> 00:09:59,329
What about a game where you're growing or making progress in an interesting way, but

167
00:09:59,329 --> 00:10:03,892
where the future outcomes are obscured enough that as a player you can't ever concretely

168
00:10:03,892 --> 00:10:06,654
see what specifically this progress will lead to?

169
00:10:07,238 --> 00:10:13,621
What about a game that has a story, but you don't need to see every piece of content to get the story?

170
00:10:13,621 --> 00:10:17,663
Say there are 10 hours of story content, but if you only play one hour,

171
00:10:17,663 --> 00:10:20,764
you've gotten just as valid of an experience as someone who plays the full 10.

172
00:10:20,764 --> 00:10:25,447
All of these sound a little bit counterintuitive in the modern design culture,

173
00:10:25,447 --> 00:10:27,007
but that's why I'm really excited.

174
00:10:27,007 --> 00:10:30,469
The bizarre and impossible-sounding goal that I've set for myself

175
00:10:30,469 --> 00:10:33,750
is to try to create a game that does all of these things.

176
00:10:34,331 --> 00:10:38,012
I don't have a good answer yet as to how exactly to do that, but here are a few games that

177
00:10:38,012 --> 00:10:40,033
I look to as inspiration.

178
00:10:40,033 --> 00:10:44,875
Desert Golfing is fun to play, you can get better, there's a score, there's new content,

179
00:10:44,875 --> 00:10:47,136
but the game never explicitly rewards you for any of it.

180
00:10:47,136 --> 00:10:51,498
The score doesn't mean anything, many people never see the new content, and if you play

181
00:10:51,498 --> 00:10:55,119
it for hours, it's because you're genuinely enjoying being in this world and whacking

182
00:10:55,119 --> 00:10:55,879
a golf ball around.

183
00:10:56,600 --> 00:11:01,603
Everything is a vast simulation that has an actual point of view about the world and lots

184
00:11:01,603 --> 00:11:06,105
of content to explore, but you can stop playing at pretty much any time and you've had just

185
00:11:06,105 --> 00:11:10,367
as valid of an experience as someone who's seen every piece of content in the game.

186
00:11:10,367 --> 00:11:11,968
Neko Atsume is sort of like this.

187
00:11:11,968 --> 00:11:15,150
If you haven't seen this, it's the mobile game where you leave out treats for cats

188
00:11:15,150 --> 00:11:17,191
and at random times cats will show up.

189
00:11:18,052 --> 00:11:23,696
It's fun to see new cats, but there is kind of an incentive to make more money and like collect the cats

190
00:11:23,696 --> 00:11:25,178
So it's not a perfect example

191
00:11:25,178 --> 00:11:30,322
But this is really a descendant of Tamagotchi which had no particular win state

192
00:11:30,322 --> 00:11:36,767
Except to feel connected with a tiny thing in your pocket and to treat it, you know with however you're feeling at the time

193
00:11:36,767 --> 00:11:42,712
It's engaging. It's compelling and it doesn't rely on future outcomes to be fun. All right, that's all I got. Thanks everyone

194
00:11:51,205 --> 00:11:54,127
Thank you, Davey.

195
00:11:54,127 --> 00:11:57,328
All right, next slide.

196
00:11:57,328 --> 00:12:01,670
Please welcome Clarice.

197
00:12:01,670 --> 00:12:09,514
Hello, everyone.

198
00:12:09,514 --> 00:12:11,815
I'm Clarice Siron, co-founder and creative director

199
00:12:11,815 --> 00:12:13,356
at Silverstring Media.

200
00:12:13,356 --> 00:12:17,017
And I want devs to see their games

201
00:12:17,017 --> 00:12:20,899
as spaces for change, healing, and contemplation.

202
00:12:22,087 --> 00:12:23,848
To that end, I would like to discuss with you today

203
00:12:23,848 --> 00:12:25,809
an underutilized but extremely on-trend narrative approach.

204
00:12:25,809 --> 00:12:27,150
And that is to embrace the occult,

205
00:12:27,150 --> 00:12:28,651
to open yourselves and your game to the dangerous, irrational

206
00:12:28,651 --> 00:12:29,511
world of magical thinking.

207
00:12:29,511 --> 00:12:29,811
Just a little bit.

208
00:12:47,341 --> 00:12:49,862
Specifically though, I'm talking about divination.

209
00:12:49,862 --> 00:12:52,343
Divination is an ancient and widely diverse form of magic

210
00:12:52,343 --> 00:12:55,505
involving the use of an object or objects

211
00:12:55,505 --> 00:12:57,826
to gain answers to questions,

212
00:12:57,826 --> 00:12:59,947
often for the purpose of preparing for the future.

213
00:12:59,947 --> 00:13:01,648
Now, if that sounds to you

214
00:13:01,648 --> 00:13:04,289
just a little bit like a simulation or a game,

215
00:13:04,289 --> 00:13:05,870
you're already getting the idea.

216
00:13:05,870 --> 00:13:06,030
Now,

217
00:13:09,667 --> 00:13:11,508
Let's take a step back for a second,

218
00:13:11,508 --> 00:13:14,149
because I think one of the reasons why more and more

219
00:13:14,149 --> 00:13:17,551
people are flocking to magic as an aesthetic, as an identity,

220
00:13:17,551 --> 00:13:19,593
and as a sincere part of their lives

221
00:13:19,593 --> 00:13:24,216
is that magic is a customizable but ultimately shared

222
00:13:24,216 --> 00:13:26,997
cultural metaphor that focuses on the experiential aspects

223
00:13:26,997 --> 00:13:28,778
of a situation rather than the technicalities.

224
00:13:28,778 --> 00:13:30,099
So let's talk about tarot for a second

225
00:13:30,099 --> 00:13:30,699
as an example of divination.

226
00:13:39,046 --> 00:13:41,008
Now, depending on your perspective,

227
00:13:41,008 --> 00:13:43,150
tarot might seem like a mystical tool

228
00:13:43,150 --> 00:13:45,092
or a bunch of delusional nonsense,

229
00:13:45,092 --> 00:13:49,616
but I think of tarot as a game, one whose purpose has shifted

230
00:13:49,616 --> 00:13:51,658
over time from gambling and entertainment

231
00:13:51,658 --> 00:13:54,080
towards contemplation and transformation.

232
00:13:54,080 --> 00:13:58,744
Now, video games have been exploring divinatory cards

233
00:13:58,744 --> 00:13:59,325
since the 80s.

234
00:14:00,160 --> 00:14:02,701
And some games have just copied it straight up.

235
00:14:02,701 --> 00:14:06,143
Others have used it as a theme or a narrative framework.

236
00:14:06,143 --> 00:14:08,684
Shout out to a game that I had the privilege of working on

237
00:14:08,684 --> 00:14:13,587
called Where the Water Tastes Like Wine.

238
00:14:13,587 --> 00:14:15,928
But how do you design for divination?

239
00:14:15,928 --> 00:14:17,889
First, you have to understand that we're designing for

240
00:14:17,889 --> 00:14:21,330
distinct, separate moments, separate from the mundane

241
00:14:21,330 --> 00:14:24,872
world, but also from the regular flow of your game.

242
00:14:24,872 --> 00:14:27,514
So guidelines one and two here help create that sense of

243
00:14:27,514 --> 00:14:28,174
separation.

244
00:14:29,515 --> 00:14:35,657
Your divinatory tool or focus object should be special and stand out from the rest of the interactable things in your game.

245
00:14:35,657 --> 00:14:42,980
As far as creating a special space, I have some good news. You've already got this somewhat covered.

246
00:14:42,980 --> 00:14:50,242
You want to invite and invoke a state of playfulness, creativity, and receptiveness, and games are already excellent at this.

247
00:14:51,295 --> 00:14:53,996
Number three, you want to put complex and interlocking

248
00:14:53,996 --> 00:14:57,397
systems and ordering structures clearly on display.

249
00:14:57,397 --> 00:14:58,097
But here's the kicker.

250
00:14:58,097 --> 00:15:01,158
These systems don't actually need to work or have

251
00:15:01,158 --> 00:15:01,959
any meaning.

252
00:15:01,959 --> 00:15:04,860
The mere suggestion of deep underlying logic

253
00:15:04,860 --> 00:15:06,980
is often enough to send our brains

254
00:15:06,980 --> 00:15:09,661
into an interpretive, pattern-recognizing overdrive.

255
00:15:09,661 --> 00:15:13,202
Number four and five are fairly self-explanatory.

256
00:15:13,202 --> 00:15:16,243
You're trying to create visual hooks for a player

257
00:15:16,243 --> 00:15:18,624
to find inspiration and hang their own personal narrative

258
00:15:18,624 --> 00:15:18,884
upon.

259
00:15:20,819 --> 00:15:22,481
Number six, introduce randomness,

260
00:15:22,481 --> 00:15:25,003
because this takes advantage of apophenia,

261
00:15:25,003 --> 00:15:27,586
which is the human tendency to seek out and find

262
00:15:27,586 --> 00:15:31,630
patterns and significance in random information.

263
00:15:31,630 --> 00:15:33,773
Number seven, ask open-ended questions.

264
00:15:33,773 --> 00:15:37,877
Stick to broad, common subjects, at least at the start.

265
00:15:37,877 --> 00:15:39,278
That'll help your players warm up.

266
00:15:41,034 --> 00:15:45,316
You can also make it clear to your players that there's no wrong answer and that it's

267
00:15:45,316 --> 00:15:47,978
up to them to decide how they perceive the moment.

268
00:15:47,978 --> 00:15:53,461
If you're curious about how to deal with an obstinate or nihilistic player, maybe check

269
00:15:53,461 --> 00:15:57,144
out a game I worked on called Glitch Hikers and see how it responds to you being a stick

270
00:15:57,144 --> 00:15:58,624
in the mud.

271
00:15:58,624 --> 00:16:03,147
You might also want to detach your divinatory moment from your game's other mechanics.

272
00:16:03,147 --> 00:16:08,671
I'm a min-maxer, personally, so I have trouble getting into a free association mindset if

273
00:16:08,671 --> 00:16:10,111
I'm worried about messing up my stats.

274
00:16:11,542 --> 00:16:15,424
And the final two, mix and match any of these rules.

275
00:16:15,424 --> 00:16:16,464
Experiment.

276
00:16:16,464 --> 00:16:18,545
Borrow others or distill your own.

277
00:16:18,545 --> 00:16:21,506
Generally, the more you use, the more hooks you have, and

278
00:16:21,506 --> 00:16:24,367
the wider success rate you'll have amongst your audience.

279
00:16:24,367 --> 00:16:26,848
But use what works for you.

280
00:16:26,848 --> 00:16:32,790
So what are some benefits to bringing a divinatory moment

281
00:16:32,790 --> 00:16:34,051
or two into your game?

282
00:16:34,051 --> 00:16:35,672
Well, for starters, it's affirming.

283
00:16:36,500 --> 00:16:39,403
A game, its creators and its players are not adversaries,

284
00:16:39,403 --> 00:16:41,824
though it sometimes can feel that way.

285
00:16:41,824 --> 00:16:43,746
Divinatory moments underscore the trust

286
00:16:43,746 --> 00:16:45,167
you're putting in your player.

287
00:16:45,167 --> 00:16:47,129
It acknowledges that we are all co-creators

288
00:16:47,129 --> 00:16:49,030
in the final experience.

289
00:16:49,030 --> 00:16:51,692
That trust is empowering,

290
00:16:51,692 --> 00:16:53,233
and it's potentially quite transformative.

291
00:16:54,287 --> 00:16:57,689
I would wager that we've all had deeply meaningful experiences

292
00:16:57,689 --> 00:16:59,091
with a video game before.

293
00:16:59,091 --> 00:17:02,273
It's probably why most of us are here right now.

294
00:17:02,273 --> 00:17:07,437
And I found that by opening a game up to,

295
00:17:07,437 --> 00:17:10,120
or rather, offering your player an opportunity

296
00:17:10,120 --> 00:17:12,081
to make a game be about what they need it

297
00:17:12,081 --> 00:17:14,783
to be about in that moment is a great way

298
00:17:14,783 --> 00:17:17,526
to increase the chance of your game

299
00:17:17,526 --> 00:17:20,348
having that meaningful transformative effect

300
00:17:20,348 --> 00:17:22,930
on others, which feels sweet when it happens.

301
00:17:24,020 --> 00:17:27,041
Best of all, this is pretty scope efficient,

302
00:17:27,041 --> 00:17:29,322
because any meanings or player interpretations

303
00:17:29,322 --> 00:17:33,563
can be mediated by abstract symbols.

304
00:17:33,563 --> 00:17:36,884
You and your game don't have to anticipate fully or understand

305
00:17:36,884 --> 00:17:40,825
that a player is dealing with the loss of their great uncle

306
00:17:40,825 --> 00:17:46,247
Billy, for example, in order to build upon it or acknowledge

307
00:17:46,247 --> 00:17:46,367
it.

308
00:17:48,698 --> 00:17:52,841
