657
00:34:00,427 --> 00:34:02,327
So when does min-maxing become a problem?

658
00:34:02,985 --> 00:34:04,626
First, when the interesting mechanics

659
00:34:04,626 --> 00:34:06,387
are much less time efficient.

660
00:34:06,387 --> 00:34:08,808
As I get older and have less time to devote to games,

661
00:34:08,808 --> 00:34:09,928
if I'm forced to make a choice

662
00:34:09,928 --> 00:34:11,649
between an interesting mechanic

663
00:34:11,649 --> 00:34:13,910
and something that lets me achieve my goals quicker,

664
00:34:13,910 --> 00:34:16,151
I almost always will take the quicker one

665
00:34:16,151 --> 00:34:16,811
out of pure practicality.

666
00:34:16,811 --> 00:34:18,912
In reality, the amount of time saved

667
00:34:18,912 --> 00:34:20,252
could be pretty minimal,

668
00:34:20,252 --> 00:34:23,534
but this psychological burden is very hard for me to ignore.

669
00:34:23,534 --> 00:34:25,595
My next problem is when single-player games

670
00:34:25,595 --> 00:34:28,796
have a very strong positive feedback loop.

671
00:34:29,440 --> 00:34:32,948
The obvious example is an option to increase experience

672
00:34:32,948 --> 00:34:35,553
or resources gained by investing in this early

