So we're at the beginning of a burgeoning movement

985
00:51:45,156 --> 00:51:46,357
of campaign games.

986
00:51:46,357 --> 00:51:49,538
We have fiscal combat in France, to run Taipei,

987
00:51:49,538 --> 00:51:51,519
and campaign games are on the threshold

988
00:51:51,519 --> 00:51:54,381
of having a major impact on political campaigns worldwide.

989
00:51:55,588 --> 00:51:59,591
So we feel proud that Corbyn Run had a real-world impact on British politics,

990
00:51:59,591 --> 00:52:03,173
and we think what we managed to do shows a path forward for developers all over the world

991
00:52:03,173 --> 00:52:07,076
to use games, to participate in political movements.

992
00:52:07,076 --> 00:52:10,698
We believe that by making an impact on the political landscape across the world,

993
00:52:10,698 --> 00:52:15,662
proving that games can be influential as more than just mass popcorn entertainment,

994
00:52:15,662 --> 00:52:18,944
we can earn games a place on the wider cultural table

995
00:52:18,944 --> 00:52:21,345
and chart a richer, more secure future for our medium.

996
00:52:21,345 --> 00:52:21,906
Thank you.

997
00:52:32,360 --> 00:52:33,500
Thank you, Rosa.

998
00:52:33,500 --> 00:52:35,621
Was that Margaret Thatcher's ghost in the game?

999
00:52:35,621 --> 00:52:37,722
Recognize the ghost anywhere.

1000
00:52:37,722 --> 00:52:45,125
All right, please welcome our final speaker, Ethan.

1001
00:52:52,831 --> 00:52:55,495
So I'm here to talk to you today about the brightest future, right?

1002
00:52:55,495 --> 00:53:02,306
It's what I call the moral imperative for trying hard, doing difficult things, and for

1003
00:53:02,306 --> 00:53:05,310
coolness basically, in both aesthetic and modality.

1004
00:53:05,785 --> 00:53:07,186
But before I get too deep into it,

1005
00:53:07,186 --> 00:53:09,387
I just wanna slap a big ol' IMO on this whole thing.

1006
00:53:09,387 --> 00:53:11,048
They asked me to give a rant, which was a mistake.

1007
00:53:11,048 --> 00:53:12,910
I intend to give one.

1008
00:53:12,910 --> 00:53:15,451
There will be some strong opinions

1009
00:53:15,451 --> 00:53:19,334
and some unsubstantiated claims, so don't at me.

1010
00:53:19,334 --> 00:53:19,994
So yeah, who am I?

1011
00:53:19,994 --> 00:53:21,255
I'm Ethan Redd.

1012
00:53:21,255 --> 00:53:25,258
I'm founder and creative lead of Virtuoso Neo Media.

1013
00:53:25,258 --> 00:53:29,561
We are a new production house focusing on bringing color

1014
00:53:29,561 --> 00:53:33,063
and fun and life-affirming charm to what we create.

1015
00:53:33,484 --> 00:53:37,066
Our current project is Blazing Legion Ignition,

1016
00:53:37,066 --> 00:53:40,228
a first-person shmup drama

1017
00:53:40,228 --> 00:53:43,550
about a four-story tall mecha and consequences.

1018
00:53:43,550 --> 00:53:45,411
And just here's some other stuff I've made

1019
00:53:45,411 --> 00:53:47,612
to get a flavor of me.

1020
00:53:47,612 --> 00:53:48,493
But enough about me.

1021
00:53:48,493 --> 00:53:49,974
I'm here to talk to you today

1022
00:53:49,974 --> 00:53:51,175
about like nothing really technical

1023
00:53:51,175 --> 00:53:53,556
or even immediately applicable,

1024
00:53:53,556 --> 00:53:55,037
but I'm here to talk to you about attitude

1025
00:53:55,037 --> 00:53:57,238
and specifically one that I've noticed

1026
00:53:57,238 --> 00:53:59,480
this last maybe two years or so

1027
00:53:59,480 --> 00:54:02,121
that I've playfully dubbed weak wave.

1028
00:54:02,641 --> 00:54:07,644
where it's like this weird demon baby of post-modernism

1029
00:54:07,644 --> 00:54:08,625
and can't-doism.

1030
00:54:08,625 --> 00:54:11,266
There's so much defeatism.

1031
00:54:11,266 --> 00:54:13,748
We have almost this fetish-type relationship

1032
00:54:13,748 --> 00:54:17,450
with failure, excessive self-deprecation, cynicism,

1033
00:54:17,450 --> 00:54:19,331
and irony for their own sake.

1034
00:54:19,331 --> 00:54:23,274
There's nothing wrong with these traits by themselves.

1035
00:54:23,274 --> 00:54:26,556
But taken together, and as a matter of course, I hate this.

1036
00:54:26,556 --> 00:54:28,397
And it is antithetical to what I think

1037
00:54:28,397 --> 00:54:30,418
art is supposed to do to me.

1038
00:54:31,680 --> 00:54:35,182
And don't get me wrong, it is very difficult to be an optimist in the year of our Lord 2018, right?

1039
00:54:35,182 --> 00:54:41,505
Um, around the world, we are facing so many rich and complicated issues.

1040
00:54:41,505 --> 00:54:45,467
And just look at this country. We have a flaming hot Cheeto for our president.

1041
00:54:45,467 --> 00:54:47,669
We have, we've seen the rise of nationalism.

1042
00:54:47,669 --> 00:54:51,370
Uh, we have almost weekly mass shootings and police brutality.

1043
00:54:51,370 --> 00:54:54,572
Uh, we have people drinking lead water, for God's sake, right?

1044
00:54:54,572 --> 00:54:58,194
Um, like, we're facing some really hard stuff.

1045
00:54:58,194 --> 00:55:00,475
It is a very scary time to be alive.

1046
00:55:00,855 --> 00:55:05,417
But that is not why we should crawl into our own shells.

1047
00:55:05,417 --> 00:55:07,518
That is why we should be bold,

1048
00:55:07,518 --> 00:55:10,419
because we are the artists, the thinkers,

1049
00:55:10,419 --> 00:55:12,320
the dreamers of dreams, right?

1050
00:55:12,320 --> 00:55:16,421
We paint the cultural landscape that everyone else lives in.

1051
00:55:16,421 --> 00:55:19,322
And the world right now needs inspiration.

1052
00:55:19,322 --> 00:55:20,443
They need to see champions.

1053
00:55:20,443 --> 00:55:21,203
They need heroes.

1054
00:55:21,203 --> 00:55:22,183
They need hope.

1055
00:55:22,735 --> 00:55:27,418
And I think we have a lot to contribute, as artists,

1056
00:55:27,418 --> 00:55:28,158
game makers, whatever.

1057
00:55:28,158 --> 00:55:32,621
We need to redefine what we consider possible,

1058
00:55:32,621 --> 00:55:34,362
both in our craft and in our own lives,

1059
00:55:34,362 --> 00:55:35,603
because people are watching.

1060
00:55:35,603 --> 00:55:38,985
I like the example of Tony Hawk landing the first 900 in 1999.

1061
00:55:38,985 --> 00:55:41,326
It was an impossible trick at the time,

1062
00:55:41,326 --> 00:55:45,269
but has since become standard in vert skating at this level,

1063
00:55:45,269 --> 00:55:47,790
because kids grew up watching him

1064
00:55:47,790 --> 00:55:50,172
doing more than what they thought was possible

1065
00:55:50,172 --> 00:55:51,212
and aspired to that level.

1066
00:55:52,033 --> 00:55:59,035
We need to do amazing things because they are difficult and because those kids and our peers are watching.

1067
00:55:59,035 --> 00:56:08,118
We need to bring our best to inspire that in others, like a heroin-addicted kung fu master still looking and seeing potential

1068
00:56:08,118 --> 00:56:13,860
in a young street urchin who would go on to be one of the greatest action filmmakers of his time

1069
00:56:13,860 --> 00:56:18,041
and inspire one of the greatest action filmmakers of all time, in my humble opinion.

1070
00:56:21,343 --> 00:56:26,206
We need to aim higher in our own work and in our fictions that we create.

1071
00:56:26,206 --> 00:56:31,189
We all love to rag on Star Trek for how campy, colorful, and weird it was back in the 60s,

1072
00:56:31,189 --> 00:56:31,689
right?

1073
00:56:31,689 --> 00:56:34,451
But it dared to ask the question, what if things were better?

1074
00:56:34,451 --> 00:56:35,892
What if we could get along?

1075
00:56:35,892 --> 00:56:40,474
What if we could invent solutions to our problems instead of just complaining about them?

1076
00:56:40,474 --> 00:56:44,897
And it inspired civil rights activists like Martin Luther King to technologists like the

1077
00:56:44,897 --> 00:56:47,539
creators of the first cell phones.

1078
00:56:48,239 --> 00:56:52,403
home computers that we all use these days, inspired real-world change.

1079
00:56:52,403 --> 00:56:58,789
We have more to contribute to this world than depression memes, samey games,

1080
00:56:58,789 --> 00:57:02,993
and just, like, being sad about stuff.

1081
00:57:02,993 --> 00:57:06,136
Like, it's hard right now, but we can improve things.

1082
00:57:06,136 --> 00:57:10,180
We can inspire people who can make a tangible impact on this world,

1083
00:57:10,180 --> 00:57:11,541
even though our work maybe doesn't.

1084
00:57:12,640 --> 00:57:16,562
We are tomorrow, and I refuse to live in a world

1085
00:57:16,562 --> 00:57:18,663
where that is a step backwards from today.

1086
00:57:18,663 --> 00:57:21,645
I refuse, Virtuoso refuses, and I invite you to as well

1087
00:57:21,645 --> 00:57:23,646
because the future is as bright as we make it.

1088
00:57:23,646 --> 00:57:24,526
Thank you, Forward Forever.

1089
00:57:40,717 --> 00:57:42,738
Wow, thank you Ethan, you crushed it.

1090
00:57:42,738 --> 00:57:45,840
That wraps it up for the Soapbox and the Independent Game Summit.

1091
00:57:45,840 --> 00:57:49,302
Please be sure to fill out your feedback forms to let us know how we did,

1092
00:57:49,302 --> 00:57:50,543
and we hope to see you again next year.

1093
00:57:50,543 --> 00:57:53,865
But before we go, let's have one final round of applause for all of our amazing speakers.

1094
00:57:53,865 --> 00:57:54,066
Thank you.

